        <Parent_String>guideboats [300232771], sport fishing vessels [300232769], yachts [300082988], competition and recreation craft [300232763], watercraft by function [300232728], watercraft by specific type [300219289], watercraft [300042940], vehicles (transportation) [300219258], Transportation Vehicles (hierarchy name) [300042929], Furnishings and Equipment (hierarchy name) [300264551], Objects Facet [300264092]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Double-ended, lapstrake rowing boats, using a single thole pin and oar with hole to fit over it, ranging in length from 16 to 23 feet, originating in the mid-19th century on the St. Lawrence River; larger examples may have sailing rigs, and are sailed without rudders.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099620/Legacy AAT data</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Úsese para bote de remo "lapstrake” de doble extremo, que emplea un tolete simple y remo con agujero para encajar sobre éste, con una longitud que oscila desde los 16 a los 23 pies, originados a mediados del siglo XIX en el Río San Lorenzo. Ejemplos mayores pueden tener aparejos de vela, y se navegan sin timones.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Te gebruiken voor aan voor- en achterzijde gelijke overnaadse roeiboten die gebruik maken van één dol en een roeispaan met een gat waarin de dol past . Ze zijn zo'n 5 tot 6 m lang en halverwege de 19e eeuw ontstaan in het gebied rond de St.Lawrence Rivier; de grotere exemplaren kunnen zeilen voeren en varen zonder roer.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>艏艉同形、魚鱗式搭接外板的船，使用單個槳栓，並於置放船槳的孔洞中划槳，約為16至23英尺長，最早出現於十九世紀的聖勞倫斯河；較大的船型可能會有帆具，且不以舵掌控行進。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
